</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="60" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[677,1210,374,560]" box="[677,1065,374,401]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis box="[677,1065,374,401]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
Radially symmetrical ovules (
<figureCitation box="[975,1057,374,401]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[677,1210,374,560]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
These rare, very small ovules (
<quantity box="[1001,1141,406,433]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5 to 3 mm</quantity>
in diameter) show a well-marked radial symmetry with evidence of three sutures of the sclerotesta (arrows, 
<figureCitation box="[677,751,501,528]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">Fig. 9J</figureCitation>
). Despite their small size, this is suggestive of affinities with medullosan pteridosperms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[675,1212,596,971]" box="[677,1068,596,622]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis box="[677,1068,596,622]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
Probable medullosan wood (
<figureCitation box="[967,1060,596,622]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[113,123,1544,1561]" captionTargetBox="[144,622,215,1500]" captionTargetId="figure-322@17.[143,391,677,1137]" captionText="FIG. 10.— Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia:A-D, Da-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607887" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607887/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">Fig. 10E</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[675,1212,596,971]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">
A few fragments of wood, sometimes fusinized, show very broad tracheids (
<quantity box="[959,1079,659,686]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="80.0" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="60.0">60-100 µm</quantity>
in diameter) with multiseriate (3 to 5-seriate) pitting on their radial walls and high multiseriate rays; they have characteristics of pteridosperm secondary xylem and may be attributed with some reservation to medullosans. This is supported by the occurrence of fragments of outer cortex, with parenchyma and sclerenchyma strands, of the 
<emphasis box="[974,1085,882,907]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">sparganum</emphasis>
- 
<typeStatus box="[1093,1140,881,908]" pageId="17" pageNumber="60">type</typeStatus>
which are characteristic of the stem and rachises of this group of seed ferns.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
